articles.description: After winning the College Football Playoff National Championship on Monday, Georgia QB Stetson Bennett took his talents to a local Raising Cane's drive-thru to serve meals to customers.
articles.headline: Georgia Bulldogs QB Stetson Bennett surprises customers at Raising Cane's Chicken restaurant

images.name: UGA's Bennett says 'you work for things like this'
images.caption: QB Stetson Bennett credits Georgia's defense for keeping them in the national championship after offensive mistakes and explains why he "bet" on himself.

articles.description: Alabama wide receivers Slade Bolden and John Metchie III will enter the NFL draft, while linebacker Henry To'o To'o, defensive lineman DJ Dale and safety Jordan Battle are returning to the team for their senior seasons.
articles.headline: Alabama Crimson Tide receivers Slade Bolden, John Metchie III to enter NFL draft; three defensive starters to return

articles.description: Georgia will be without both of its leading rushers, junior Zamir White and senior James Cook, in addition to safety Lewis Cine when it tries to defend its national title in 2022. All three players have declared for the NFL draft.
articles.headline: Georgia Bulldogs leading rushers Zamir White, James Cook and top tackler Lewis Cine declare for NFL draft

article.description:
Kicker Dan Nystrom became the Big Ten Conference's all-time leading scorer as Minnesota shook off a season-ending four-game losing streak with a 29-14
victory over Arkansas in the Gaylord Hotels Music City Bowl.
article.headline: Minnesota kicker Big Ten's all-time leading scorer
article.linkText: Bowl victory over Arkansas music to Minnesota's ears
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- If Minnesota coach Glen Mason had his
way, Dan Nystrom would not have been the Most Valuable Player of
the Music City Bowl.

	   Nystrom tied an NCAA record by kicking five field goals as
Minnesota upset Arkansas 29-14 on Monday for the Golden
Gophers' first bowl victory since 1985.

<photo1>

	   "I wish he was standing next to me and we were scoring
touchdowns. I've got a lot of respect for this guy. He's had some
slumps, and he's had periods where he kicked well,'' Mason said of
the senior kicker. "He had a great day today.''

	   The Gophers (8-5) had lost three straight bowls since beating
Clemson in the 1985 Independence Bowl. They came into the game
having blown their best start since 1961 by losing their final four
games of the regular season and finishing seventh in the Big Ten.

	   Arkansas (9-5, No. 25 AP), the SEC's Western Division champ, was seeking
its first 10-win season since going 10-2 in 1989. But Minnesota,
with only two senior starters, dominated the Razorbacks. Arkansas
is now 1-10 in its last 11 bowl games.

	   The Gophers controlled the ball and forced four turnovers,
including two interceptions by senior cornerback Michael Lehan.
Asad Abdul-Khaliq threw for a touchdown in the third quarter and
Thomas Tapeh added a 33-yard run in the fourth.

	   "If Danny wasn't on the top of his game, then it would've been
a lot tougher to win,'' said Abdul-Khaliq, who was 16-of-31 for 216
yards passing.

	   Nystrom bailed the Gophers out in the first half, when they
repeatedly stalled near the goal line. He had kicks of 24, 45, 21
and 22 yards in the first half for a 12-7 halftime lead and added a
29-yarder in the fourth. His first three kicks made him the Big
Ten's career field-goal leader, passing Travis Dorsch, who had 68
at Purdue.

	   Told about Mason's comments, Nystrom quickly agreed that he'd
rather stand beside the coach watching the Golden Gophers score
touchdowns.

	   "I'm surprised to win the MVP. Kickers never win MVP,'' he
said. "It's a great ending for my career.''

	   The senior became the fifth kicker with five field goals in a
bowl game and the first since Dec. 28, 1995 when Texas A&M's Kyle
Bryant did it in the Alamo Bowl against Michigan.

	   Nystrom might have had six field goals, but Minnesota chose to
go for it on fourth-and-5 from the Arkansas 25 and turned the ball
over on downs with 2:46 left.

	   Minnesota's failure to score touchdowns allowed the Razorbacks
to stay close, despite the Gophers holding the ball for more than
38 minutes and having 434 total yards of offense compared to the
Razorbacks' 288.

	   "We're better than that,'' Arkansas coach Houston Nutt said.
"We didn't perform like we should have. We didn't know where we
were on the field defensively. We're usually so aggressive.''

	   The Razorbacks started strong, putting together a 74-yard
scoring drive on their first possession. The SEC's best rushing
team went to the air as Matt Jones started with a 29-yard pass to
Richard Smith and capped the drive with a 2-yard TD pass to George
Wilson.

	   That turned out to be their best possession of the game,
however, as they rushed for only 80 yards, well below their average
of 226.9 per game.

	   Nutt pulled Jones in the fourth quarter, putting in Ryan
Sorahan. It was too late, and his first drive ended when Fred
Talley fumbled at midfield.

	   Minnesota had no trouble moving the ball against an Arkansas
defense ranked 40th in the nation. The Golden Gophers had drives of
10, 13 and 10 plays, but were stopped three times inside the
Arkansas 7 before halftime.

	   Arkansas had a chance to take the lead just before halftime when
Jones found Smith in the end zone for what would have been a
31-yard TD catch, but Smith was ruled out of bounds.
